social_posts.post_text:
🫡 The first year in real estate is always a rough one. Didn’t sell my first house until about 5-6 months in. If I’ve learned anything during my time in the business it’s that perseverance will always pay off in the long run. Always put your best effort out there and don’t stress about things you can’t control. 

Anybody that knows me or has worked with me understands that I am passionate about this industry. I encourage anybody starting a new gig to grind and just do your best. Trust that God’s path will lead you to where you’re meant to be!

I wish you all the best in your business and personal lives as we head into a brand new year. Cheers friends! 🥂 Love y’all.

INTEREST RATES ⬇️ A drop in rates is what we all want to see in the real estate world. Hopefully as we continue on into 2023 we will see more good news and more of a friendly scenario for home buyers. I imagine that when we do see the fed pivot away from rate hikes then, in turn, we will see mortgage rates have more of a significant drop. I predict that when this does happen there will be much more demand from consumers looking to get back into the market. Both investors and primary home buyers. Until then, stay patient and stay positive. 

If you’ve ever got any questions about the real estate market or buying/selling shoot me a message anytime. 📲 @clarkmcfarland

⚠️40 year mortgages are a bad idea. 

First of all, a longer term mortgage will come with an inflated interest rate along with 10 more years to pay that interest to the lien holder. 

Second of all, with a higher interest rate the benefit of saving a $100-200 on your payment every month DOES NOT make sense in the long run. 

My personal opinion is to better prepare yourself for a traditional type of loan product. Every buyers situation is different I understand that, but there is no reason to extend your loan term 10 years to save yourself a couple hundred bucks a month. If that’s the case put off the home search until you’re prepared!

I will never be the most fit person in the gym. I will never be the best at golf (or even good). I will never be the best at playing the guitar. I will never be the best at making social media content. And a million other things. But I’ll do my best at these or any other things I strive to accomplish in this life, for me. 

I’ve had many epiphanies over the past year about life and how to live it. Practicing gratitude and thanking God for the abundance in my life every day is just one of them. 

Wishing you all the best, and all the positive vibes. Love y’all.🤘🏼

🏡Just like my passion for helping people buy/sell real estate, I’ve found joy in being more involved in the investment side of real estate over the past year. Switching from a long term rental vision to a short term rental/Airbnb vision is something I was totally against 18 months ago. “Too much work. You have to buy furniture. People break things. It’s risky…etc” is what I would say. 

The journey from just a vision of what the vibe of a home can be to actually accommodating guests is so fulfilling. Anybody who knows me would laugh at the idea of me fixing something home related, but being more hands on and learning to fix and install things has been really cool. I guess the gist of this caption is to never put yourself in a box and don’t be afraid to be open minded. Try new things. Always be a student. And use YouTube to learn stuffs. Cheers y’all.

⚠️ Not only is there still a shortage of supply of homes for sale, that problem is compounded by the fact that a large amount of homeowners purchased when rates were at historic lows. 

According to Goldman Sachs, 72% of homeowners have a mortgage rate under 4% and 28% of homeowners have a mortgage rate under 3%. The cost of a move-up home is not only a higher price point, but mortgage rates have caused the purchasing power of home buyers to deteriorate. This has created a significant number of home sellers who do not feel a need to sell their primary residence.

🏠📉 What’s a 2/1 Buydown mortgage? It’s a type of home loan that offers initial interest rate reductions. With this product, you pay a reduced interest rate for the first two years, followed by a slightly higher rate for the remaining term. 💰💸 It can help make monthly payments more manageable in the early years of homeownership. 🏡💼 Consider it if you want lower initial payments and expect your income to increase over time!

The appreciation of real estate that we saw during the pandemic years was unprecedented, but there is definitely something to take away from the last few years. 

Anybody who had purchased a property in the years before the pandemic suddenly found themselves in a position of opportunity due to massive amounts of new equity in their homes from appreciation. 

You never should never buy a home with an unrealistic expectation of appreciation over a few short years, but those that did pull the trigger unknowingly put themselves in a great situation moving forward, while those who were waiting on prices to drop got left behind. This is typically what happens to buyers who get ‘paralysis by analysis’ as real estate has historically and continually gone up in value. 

Buy real estate and wait. 🔑

🏡📈 Exploring the Real Estate Cycle: From Boom to Bust! 📉🏠

🔍 Curious about the 4 key phases of the cycle of real estate? Let's break it down:

1️⃣ Recovery: 🌱 Prices and demand are on the rise, it's a seller's market!
2️⃣ Expansion: 📈 The market is at its highest, but be cautious - it won't last forever!
3️⃣ Contraction/Hyper supply: 📉 Demand slows, prices stabilize or drop, great time for buyers!
4️⃣ Recession: The market hits bottom, but opportunities for savvy investors emerge!

Where do you think we are in the cycle?

Stay informed, make smart choices! 🤓💼

When buying a home, make sure you are comfortable with having the original mortgage payment for an extended period of time. The opportunity to refinance to a lower rate will just be icing on the cake when the time comes. 

Your mortgage can also INCREASE the year after purchase due to increases in taxable value and increases in insurance premiums‼️

💡 Please keep these things in mind during your home search and have your realtor/loan officer accurately educate you if needed.

🏡My experience with Airbnb guests is that they are generally very respectful with communication and leave the properties in great shape. It’s fulfilling providing a stay the guests enjoy!

📋 On the other hand, Airbnb hosts get a lot of heat on social media for having some rules in place upon checkout. The reasoning behind having checkout duties is to set a precedent. My opinion is that when a guest knows they need to gather dirty towels or sheets, remove trash..etc. then the home won’t be left a total wreck. Between 11:00 a.m. checkout and a same day 4:00 p.m. check-in a lot needs to be done by the cleaning service to keep the property up to expectation of guests. A trashed property puts the home in jeopardy of not being ready to roll. 

Let me know if you have any funny Airbnb stories you can share in the comments! 😂

A quick glimpse into my brain. 🧠 One of my goals for 2023 was to read 1 book a month. I’ve never been a big reader whatsoever, but I can honestly say I’ve created a new habit that is pretty satisfying. Being unplugged for even as little as 20-30 minutes as often as you can will do the brain a lot of good in my opinion. 

Ever since I lost my Dad I’ve been infatuated with why the brain works the way it does when we go through difficult times, or when things are going great. Several of these books helped me to better understand myself, and create better mental and physical habits. Psychology, spiritual enlightenment, and obviously personal finance/real estate are the trend here. Be forever a student of life and never a know it all. 

Here are some of my favorites from this year if you’re looking for some good reads 📚 

1. Atomic Habits - James Clear
2. The Power of Now - Eckhart Tolle
3. The Monk who Sold His Ferrari - Robin Sharma
4. The Psychology of Money - Morgan Housel
5. Greenlights - Matthew McConaughey
6. Die With Zero - Bill Perkins 
7. The Millionaire Next Door 
8. The Creative Act - Rick Rubin
9. Ego is The Enemy - Ryan Holiday
10. The Blue Mind - Wallace Nichols

social_posts.post_text:
Let’s face it, 3% interest rates are not coming back. BUT the 8% rates are gone. Consumers are adjusting accordingly to the new environment just like they always have in the past. Keep in mind, for every 1% drop in interest rates your purchasing power will increase roughly 10%. Buying the move-up home was a bad idea in my opinion over the past year, but with the current outlook of the market that step in a buyer’s journey is now more feasible. 

1. The good news is that interest rates have dropped and are forecasted to come down more during 2024. 
2. Less competition. Buyers have more negotiation power to land a lower sales  price and/or concessions towards closing costs to potentially buy down the interest rate or have less cash to close on closing day. 
3. Being priced out of the market due to high rates could be a thing of the past. As rates drop your purchasing power increases which provides the ability to afford more home if you need it.
